    "dcterms:abstract": [
        {
            "@language": "ja",
            "@value": "3・11後、ぼくに出来る、無理のない支援はないものかと思い続けた。二年後の東北を歩き、いまだ津波の残した災害の激しさ、なまなましい景色を眼の前にした。そこで、津波に呑まれて亡くなった人たちの幽霊が、生き延びた人たちを慰めていた話を聞き、ぎりぎりの救いまでも消えていくように、幽霊も出なくなって寂しいという老人のこころに語りかけたいと思った。一人芝居でその悲しみと希望を描けないかと思った時、佐々木愛さんの、苦しさを押しのける、軽快な笑い声が聞こえたのだった。\r\n愛さんの秋田弁を耳にしながら、「幽霊も出なくなって寂しい物語」を、一人芝居として書きはじめた。それは、超後期高齢者の愛の物語である。",
            "is_public": true,
            "property_id": 19,
            "property_label": "Abstract",
            "type": "literal"
        },
        {
            "@language": "en",
            "@value": "After 3/11, I kept wondering if there was any reasonable support I can provide. Walking in the Tohoku region two years later, I was faced with the intensity of the disaster still remaining by the tsunami, and the vivid landscape in front of me.\r\nThere, I heard the ghosts of those who were swallowed by the tsunami in the stories comforting those who survived, and I felt that I wanted to speak to the heart of an old man who was sad when saved at the last minute and the ghosts no longer appearing to him. When I was wondering if I could depict that sadness and hope with a one-man play, I heard the light-hearted laughter of Sasaki Ai overcoming her struggles.\r\nWhile listening to Ms. Ai’s Akita dialect, I began to write the “sad story where even the ghosts no longer appear” as a one-man show. This is the story of the love of an elderly person of extremely advanced age.",
            "is_public": true,
            "property_id": 19,
            "property_label": "Abstract",
            "type": "literal"
        }
    ],
